e Germanic regions: Carolingian France, late Anglo-Saxon England, and Ottonian Saxony. Each of these moments exhibits distinct yet interconnected stages of conversion and reform, different stages of cultural amalgamation out of which various possibilities for female subject formation emerge. The book also connects with current conversations about the interrelatedness of power, knowledge, and subjectivity, opening new possibilities for the study of women in early ecclesiastical cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChristian literature, English (Middle)xHistory and criticism. 0aChristian literature, Latin (Medieval and modern)xHistory and criticism. 0aChristianity and literaturezGermanyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aEnglish literatureyOld English, ca. 450-1100xHistory and criticism. 0aWomen in ChristianityzGermanyxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aHistory : Medieval Studies. 4aLiterature : Literature. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Christianity. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079147813440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791478134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791478134/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles